DIPA is cherished for its diverse properties, making it an ideal solvent, emollient, and skin-conditioning agent. Its low viscosity and exceptional spreading abilities have made it a popular ingredient in lotions, creams, and other skincare products, significantly enhancing their texture and overall sensory experience. Furthermore, DIPA acts as a lubricant and contributes to the improved absorption of other beneficial ingredients into the skin.



The North American market for diisopropyl adipate (DIPA) is expected to grow from $189.01 million in 2022 to $296.42 million by 2029, at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 6.79%. The market is being driven by the increasing demand for DIPA in a variety of applications, including personal care, pharmaceuticals, and agrochemicals.



DIPA is a colorless, odorless, and tasteless liquid that is used as a plasticizer, solvent, and lubricant. It is a versatile compound with a wide range of applications. In the personal care industry, DIPA is used in a variety of products, including lotions, creams, and shampoos. It helps to keep the skin soft and smooth, and it also prevents the products from drying out. In the pharmaceutical industry, DIPA is used as a solvent for a variety of drugs. It also helps to improve the solubility of drugs in water, which makes them easier to absorb by the body. In the agrochemical industry, DIPA is used as a plasticizer for PVC films. It helps to make the films more flexible and durable.



The major global manufacturers of DIPA include Croda International, SC Johnson, Lubrizol, Seqens (Chemoxy International), Stearinerie Dubois, Weifang Bincheng Chemical, Weifang Hansheng Chemical, Weifang DEMETER Chemical, and Weifang Limin Chemical. In 2022, the world's top three vendors accounted for approximately 45.85% of the revenue.



The North American market for DIPA is dominated by the United States and Canada. The United States is the largest market for DIPA in the region, followed by Canada. The growth of the market in North America is being driven by the increasing demand for DIPA in the personal care and pharmaceutical industries.

